---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../styles/global.css';
import ArtifactGallery from '../components/ArtifactGallery.astro';
import SearchIndex from '../components/SearchIndex.astro';
import AgentRunLedger from '../components/AgentRunLedger.astro';
import RoadmapBoard from '../components/RoadmapBoard.astro';
import PretextOracle from '../components/PretextOracle.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Nocturne Signal" description="A dark techno-oracle GitHub Pages site for presenting projects, agent workflows, artifacts, and operating principles with verified static-site boundaries.">
  <main>
    <section class="hero cockpit-shell" id="top">
      <nav class="nav" aria-label="Primary navigation">
        <a class="brand" href="#top" aria-label="Nocturne Signal home"><span class="brand-mark">N</span><span>Nocturne Signal</span></a>
        <div class="nav-links"><a href="#context">Context</a><a href="#lab">Lab</a><a href="#panels">Panels</a><a href="#proof">Proof</a><a href="#boundaries">Boundaries</a></div>
      </nav>

      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <p class="eyebrow">Static AgentSite · product-cockpit recipe · no-payment mode</p>
          <h1>Operate from the dark edge of the stack</h1>
          <p class="hero-lede">Nocturne Signal is a static command surface for AI experiments, agent workflows, repo artifacts, and technical field notes — sharp enough to feel alive, but constrained enough to stay public-safe and deployable on GitHub Pages.</p>
          <p class="workflow-lede">The page explains the user-facing workflow first, then gives reviewers the operating context, repo-local proof, and approval boundaries needed to evaluate the next step safely.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions"><a class="button primary" href="#signal">Inspect the signal</a><a class="button secondary" href="https://github.com/castiliad/nocturne-signal">View source</a></div>
        </div>

        <aside class="cockpit-card hero-panel signal-panel" id="signal" aria-label="Nocturne Signal kinetic typography cockpit">
          <div class="panel-header"><span class="pulse-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span><strong>pretext / signal</strong></div>
          <PretextOracle />
          <div class="status-stack compact-status"><div><span>Delivery</span><strong>Static GitHub Pages</strong></div>
<div><span>Guardrails</span><strong>No analytics · no tracking · no fake proof</strong></div></div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section split-section" id="context">
      <div>
        <div class="section-kicker">Operating context</div>
        <h2>What decision this page helps visitors make</h2>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>Nocturne Signal presents AI/operator experiments as public-safe static artifacts: crisp enough for technical collaborators, constrained enough for future agents to maintain without inventing claims.</p>
        <p>Visitors should understand the core promise first — a sharp operator-lab surface with repo-backed proof — before they inspect the deeper archive of contracts, QA gates, roadmap notes, search indexes, and run history.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section evidence-strip" id="evidence-strip" aria-label="Copy evidence strip">
      <div class="evidence-strip-heading">
        <div class="section-kicker">Copy evidence strip</div>
        <h2>Every strong line gets paired with a verifiable artifact.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="evidence-strip-track">
        <article class="evidence-strip-card">
          <span class="evidence-strip-label">Claim 01</span>
          <h3>Static GitHub Pages delivery</h3>
          <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> Static deploy evidence — GitHub Pages publishes the built output and npm run verify:deploy checks the live URL after deployment.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="evidence-strip-card">
          <span class="evidence-strip-label">Claim 02</span>
          <h3>Public-safe artifact and project presentation</h3>
          <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> Agent contracts — .agent/site.contract.yaml and .agent/brand.contract.yaml define the mission, allowed claims, forbidden claims, visual posture, and approval boundaries.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="evidence-strip-card">
          <span class="evidence-strip-label">Claim 03</span>
          <h3>Repo-local QA and deploy verification</h3>
          <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> Local QA gates — npm run qa and npm run qa:full validate contracts, claims, links, generated indexes, build output, and browser-visible behavior.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="evidence-strip-card">
          <span class="evidence-strip-label">Claim 04</span>
          <h3>Agent-maintainable contracts and runbooks</h3>
          <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> Static deploy evidence — GitHub Pages publishes the built output and npm run verify:deploy checks the live URL after deployment.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section boundary-section trust-boundaries" id="boundaries">
      <div class="section-kicker">Boundaries before proof</div>
      <h2>Trust the signal because the page refuses fake proof.</h2>
      <div class="boundary-list"><p><strong>Not claimed:</strong> fake customer quoted endorsements.</p>
<p><strong>Not claimed:</strong> fake usage metrics, benchmark numbers, or live private telemetry.</p>
<p><strong>Approval required:</strong> analytics, cookies, tracking pixels, forms, payments, lead capture, external scripts, or private project details.</p></div>
    </section>

    <section class="section proof-trail" id="proof-trail">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <div class="section-kicker">Featured proof trail</div>
        <h2>One claim, traced through the static operating envelope.</h2>
        <p>Instead of asking visitors to trust a wall of cards, the page now spotlights the verification chain future agents should preserve.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="proof-trail-grid">
        <article class="cockpit-card"><span class="card-label">01 · Claim</span><h3>Static GitHub Pages delivery</h3><p>The site is a public static surface, not a live private dashboard or analytics collector.</p></article>
        <article class="cockpit-card"><span class="card-label">02 · Contract</span><h3>Approval boundaries</h3><p>Repo contracts define allowed claims, forbidden claims, no-payment mode, and edits that require explicit approval.</p></article>
        <article class="cockpit-card"><span class="card-label">03 · QA</span><h3>Local gates</h3><p>Contract, claim, SEO, link, artifact, roadmap, index, ledger, layout, and build checks run before handoff.</p></article>
        <article class="cockpit-card"><span class="card-label">04 · Deploy</span><h3>Live verification</h3><p>The deploy verifier checks the GitHub Pages URL for expected text after publication.</p></article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section primary-surface-layout" id="primary-surface" data-primary-surface="artifacts">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <div class="section-kicker">Primary surface</div>
        <h2>Browse the proof first; open the archive only when needed.</h2>
        <p>The artifact gallery stays visible as the primary inspection surface. Search, roadmap, and run history are still available, but they no longer dominate the landing-page rhythm.</p>
      </div>
      <ArtifactGallery />
    </section>

    <section class="section secondary-modules" id="secondary-modules" aria-label="Secondary static proof modules">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <div class="section-kicker">Inspectable archive</div>
        <h2>Deep systems stay reachable without becoming the whole story.</h2>
        <p>Open these panels when you want the full static site brain, improvement board, or orchestration trail.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="secondary-module-stack">
        <details class="secondary-module" data-secondary-module>
          <summary><span>Static intelligence pack</span><strong>Search contracts, recipes, proof files, roadmap items, and runs.</strong></summary>
          <SearchIndex />
        </details>
        <details class="secondary-module" data-secondary-module>
          <summary><span>Local-first roadmap</span><strong>Inspect the improvement board without implying repo persistence.</strong></summary>
          <RoadmapBoard />
        </details>
        <details class="secondary-module" data-secondary-module>
          <summary><span>Agent run ledger</span><strong>Open the orchestration trail, deploy evidence, and checks when needed.</strong></summary>
          <AgentRunLedger />
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section pattern-lab" id="lab">
      <div class="pattern-lab-hero">
        <div>
          <div class="section-kicker">Static Site Pattern Lab</div>
          <h2>A canvas for testing skills, recipes, and agent-built polish.</h2>
        </div>
        <p>Nocturne Signal now tracks the experiments we want to try, the skills that can drive them, and the promotion rules that keep the live page sharp instead of chaotic.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="experiment-grid" aria-label="Static site experiments">
        <article class="experiment-card featured-experiment">
          <span class="experiment-status">Next · ready</span>
          <h3>Proof-chain diagram</h3>
          <p>Turn the claim → contract → QA → deploy path into a visual system map so visitors understand the AgentSite operating envelope faster.</p>
          <dl><div><dt>Skills</dt><dd>architecture-diagram · p5js</dd></div><div><dt>Recipes</dt><dd>copy-evidence-strip · primary-surface-layout</dd></div><div><dt>Promotion test</dt><dd>Improves clarity without adding runtime complexity.</dd></div></dl>
        </article>
        <article class="experiment-card">
          <span class="experiment-status">Motion study</span>
          <h3>Kinetic signal layer</h3>
          <p>Use restrained motion to make the command surface feel alive while preserving reduced-motion support and readable content.</p>
          <dl><div><dt>Skills</dt><dd>pretext · gsap · p5js</dd></div><div><dt>Recipes</dt><dd>product-cockpit</dd></div><div><dt>Promotion test</dt><dd>Delight increases; contrast, performance, and accessibility stay clean.</dd></div></dl>
        </article>
        <article class="experiment-card">
          <span class="experiment-status">Design bakeoff</span>
          <h3>One section, three visual systems</h3>
          <p>Render the same proof section as dark cockpit, editorial ledger, and premium SaaS to learn what each approach communicates.</p>
          <dl><div><dt>Skills</dt><dd>claude-design · popular-web-designs · sketch</dd></div><div><dt>Recipes</dt><dd>product-cockpit · editorial-ledger</dd></div><div><dt>Promotion test</dt><dd>The best variant wins on scan speed, credibility, and taste.</dd></div></dl>
        </article>
        <article class="experiment-card">
          <span class="experiment-status">Media pack</span>
          <h3>Generated visual asset gallery</h3>
          <p>Create a consistent Nocturne visual pack and publish prompts, model notes, and selected outputs as inspectable artifacts.</p>
          <dl><div><dt>Skills</dt><dd>swarmui-zimage-api · comfy-workbench · codex-imagegen</dd></div><div><dt>Recipes</dt><dd>artifact-gallery · search-index</dd></div><div><dt>Promotion test</dt><dd>Assets add atmosphere without replacing verifiable proof.</dd></div></dl>
        </article>
        <article class="experiment-card">
          <span class="experiment-status">Video trail</span>
          <h3>Site-to-video trailer</h3>
          <p>Use the site itself as source material for a short launch-style explainer that demonstrates HTML-as-motion-design workflows.</p>
          <dl><div><dt>Skills</dt><dd>hyperframes · gsap</dd></div><div><dt>Recipes</dt><dd>agent-run-ledger · artifact-gallery</dd></div><div><dt>Promotion test</dt><dd>The video becomes a static artifact with source, render notes, and QA evidence.</dd></div></dl>
        </article>
        <article class="experiment-card">
          <span class="experiment-status">Learning loop</span>
          <h3>Request inbox and lesson ledger</h3>
          <p>Track future ideas, decisions, failures, and wins so the site becomes a living notebook for agent-maintained static pages.</p>
          <dl><div><dt>Skills</dt><dd>agentsite-workflow · subagent-driven-development</dd></div><div><dt>Recipes</dt><dd>feature-request-inbox · agent-run-ledger · chief-of-staff-briefing</dd></div><div><dt>Promotion test</dt><dd>Useful signal accumulates without burying the landing page.</dd></div></dl>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="skill-matrix" aria-label="Skill to site capability matrix">
        <div class="matrix-heading">
          <div class="section-kicker">Skill matrix</div>
          <h3>Which skills unlock which static-site behaviors?</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="matrix-grid">
          <div><strong>pretext</strong><span>Kinetic typography, text fields, terminal aura, cursor-reactive hero surfaces.</span></div>
          <div><strong>p5js</strong><span>Generative diagrams, proof constellations, particle/radar systems, interactive canvases.</span></div>
          <div><strong>gsap</strong><span>Scroll reveals, proof-chain motion, panel transitions, and reduced-motion-aware polish.</span></div>
          <div><strong>architecture-diagram</strong><span>Static SVG maps for contracts, QA gates, deploy flows, and recipe relationships.</span></div>
          <div><strong>hyperframes</strong><span>HTML-to-video trailers, animated walkthroughs, social clips, and motion-design artifacts.</span></div>
          <div><strong>swarmui-zimage-api</strong><span>Generated image packs, style explorations, model comparisons, and prompt-to-artifact galleries.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="promotion-rules">
        <div class="section-kicker">Promotion rule</div>
        <p>An experiment graduates into the primary page only when it improves <strong>clarity</strong>, <strong>delight</strong>, or <strong>maintainability</strong> without violating static safety: no analytics, no forms, no backend, no fake proof, and no private data.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section audience" id="audience">
      <div class="section-kicker">Audience named in the brief</div>
      <h2>Built for the people who need the workflow explained clearly.</h2>
      <ul><li>Technical collaborators reviewing AI/operator experiments</li>
<li>Hiring or project leads who need a credible technical signal without marketing fluff</li>
<li>Future agents maintaining the site from contracts, QA gates, and deploy evidence</li></ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section cockpit-grid-section" id="panels">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <div class="section-kicker">Cockpit panels</div>
        <h2>Status, workflow, proof, and constraints in one scan.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="cockpit-grid">
        <article class="cockpit-card">
          <span class="card-label">01 · Signal</span>
          <h3>Signal over spectacle</h3>
          <p>The site leads with a high-contrast command-center surface: terse copy, repo-backed proof, and a kinetic text field that feels technical instead of decorative.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cockpit-card">
          <span class="card-label">02 · Systems</span>
          <h3>Systems you can inspect</h3>
          <p>Project cards, artifact trails, run ledgers, and public-safe search surfaces make the site feel operational without pretending to stream live private telemetry.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="cockpit-card">
          <span class="card-label">03 · Handoff</span>
          <h3>Agent-maintainable by design</h3>
          <p>Contracts, runbooks, QA scripts, and GitHub Pages verification give future agents a safe operating envelope for edits and deploys.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section artifact-section" id="proof">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <div class="section-kicker">Proof artifacts</div>
        <h2>Evidence a future maintainer can verify.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="artifact-grid">
        <article>
          <span class="artifact-path">Repo-verifiable artifact</span>
          <h3>Static deploy evidence</h3>
          <p>GitHub Pages publishes the built output and npm run verify:deploy checks the live URL after deployment.</p>
        </article>

        <article>
          <span class="artifact-path">Repo-verifiable artifact</span>
          <h3>Agent contracts</h3>
          <p>.agent/site.contract.yaml and .agent/brand.contract.yaml define the mission, allowed claims, forbidden claims, visual posture, and approval boundaries.</p>
        </article>

        <article>
          <span class="artifact-path">Repo-verifiable artifact</span>
          <h3>Local QA gates</h3>
          <p>npm run qa and npm run qa:full validate contracts, claims, links, generated indexes, build output, and browser-visible behavior.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section cta" id="cta">
      <div><div class="section-kicker">Safe next step</div><h2>Inspect the signal</h2><p>Use the cockpit panels, repository contracts, and QA commands before changing claims, scope, payments, analytics, or deployment settings.</p></div>
      <a class="button primary" href="#signal">Inspect the signal</a>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
